CM Trivial dipole + NT card matching demo (US 20 m ham band)
CM
CM Geometry: half-wave dipole in free space, sized so the NEC2 model
CM resonates near 14.175 MHz, the centre of the US 20 m amateur band
CM (14.000 - 14.350 MHz).  Theoretical thin-wire feedpoint impedance at
CM that resonance is approximately 73 + j0 Ohms.
CM
CM Length derivation:
CM   target centre f = 14.175 MHz  ->  lambda = 300/14.175 = 21.164 m
CM   NEC2 thin-wire resonant ratio for r = 1 mm is L/lambda ~ 0.4850
CM   total length L = 0.4850 * 21.164 = 10.264 m
CM   half-length     = 5.132 m, placed along the y axis at z = 0
CM   21 segments    -> segment length 0.489 m ~ lambda/43, well within
CM   the NEC2 lambda/10 segmentation guideline.  Odd count puts the
CM   driven element at tag 1 segment 11.
CM
CM Match network: an NT card between the dipole feed segment (tag 1,
CM seg 11) and a small isolated port wire (tag 2, seg 1) implements a
CM two-port lossless L-network that transforms the 73 Ohm dipole feed
CM to 50 Ohms at the EX voltage source.  Topology read from port 1 to
CM port 2: shunt C, series L.  Design reactances:
CM   Q  = sqrt(73/50 - 1) = 0.6782
CM   Xp = -R_high / Q     = -107.64 Ohm  (shunt C on the 73 Ohm side)
CM   Xs = Q * R_low       =  +33.91 Ohm  (series L into the 50 Ohm side)
CM
CM Y matrix in Siemens; NEC2 does not rescale NT entries with frequency,
CM so the lumped equivalence is exact at 14.175 MHz only.  Across the
CM sweep the dipole reactance also drifts, so the cleanest 50 + j0
CM reading lands at the geometric resonance.  Y21 is implied reciprocal:
CM   Y11 = 0 - 0.02020 j   Y12 = 0 + 0.02949 j   Y22 = 0 - 0.02949 j
CM
CM Port wire (tag 2): a 0.1 m stub placed 100 m off axis, electrically
CM tiny (~ 0.005 lambda) so its own radiation is negligible compared to
CM the dipole driven through the NT.
CM
CM Sweep: full US 20 m band, 14.000 - 14.350 MHz, 15 points x 25 kHz.
CM
CM Visual: the OpenGL structure view draws a filled magenta
CM quadrilateral with two port-connector lines between segments 1.11
CM and 2.1, exercising the ntyp 1 polygon fill batch.
CE
GW 1 21   0.000 -5.132  0.000   0.000  5.132  0.000  0.001
GW 2  1 100.000 -0.050  0.000 100.000  0.050  0.000  0.001
GE 0
NT 1 11 2 1  0.0 -0.02020  0.0  0.02949  0.0 -0.02949
EX 0  2  1  0  1.0  0.0
FR 0 15 0 0  14.000  0.025
RP 0 19 37 1000  0.0  0.0  10.0 10.0
EN
